==English==
===Etymology===
First attested in [[w:1604|1604]], in nowadays sense since [[w:1665|1665]], from [[French]] [[idiosyncrasie]], from [[Greek]] [[idiosynkrasia]] "personal temperament'', from [[idios]] ''personal, private'' (see also [[idiot]], [[idiom]]) + [[synkrasis]] ''temperament'', from [[syn-]] ''together'' + [[krasis]] ''mixture''.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/ˌɪdi.əˈsɪŋkɹəsi/}}

===Noun===
'''idiosyncrasy''' (''plural:'' '''ideosyncrasies''')

#a way of behaving or thinking that is characteristic of a person
#language or behaviour that is particular to an individual or group

====Synonyms====
*[[foible]]
*[[mannerism]]
*[[peccadillos]]

